## Rationale and usage

Reading data out of a `ReadOnlySequence<T>`  (such as those returned via `System.IO.Pipelines.ReadResult`) is difficult. Writing performant, correct logic that handles data spanning multiple discontinuous segments is hard.

`BufferReader<T>` wraps a `ReadOnlySequence<T>` and provides methods for reading binary and text data with a focus on performance and minimal or zero heap allocations.

This proposal is based on code developed in CoreFXlabs

Take the [sample code](https://gist.github.com/terrajobst/7e04b424ab279e711eece8f6b1c233d8#file-sample5-cs-L47-L84) from the [blog post](https://blogs.msdn.microsoft.com/dotnet/2018/07/09/system-io-pipelines-high-performance-io-in-net/) introducing System.IO.Pipelines:

``` C#
async Task ReadPipeAsync(PipeReader reader)
{
    while (true)
    {
        ReadResult result = await reader.ReadAsync();

        ReadOnlySequence<byte> buffer = result.Buffer;
        SequencePosition? position = null;

        do 
        {
            // Look for a EOL in the buffer
            position = buffer.PositionOf((byte)'\n');

            if (position != null)
            {
                // Process the line
                ProcessLine(buffer.Slice(0, position.Value));
                
                // Skip the line + the \n character (basically position)
                buffer = buffer.Slice(buffer.GetPosition(1, position.Value));
            }
        }
        while (position != null);

        // Tell the PipeReader how much of the buffer we have consumed
        reader.AdvanceTo(buffer.Start, buffer.End);

        // Stop reading if there's no more data coming
        if (result.IsCompleted)
        {
            break;
        }
    }

    // Mark the PipeReader as complete
    reader.Complete();
}
```

Dealing with slicing and `SequencePosition` is awkward. With `BufferReader<byte>` the sample would be written like this:

``` C#
async Task ReadPipeAsync(PipeReader reader)
{
    while (true)
    {
        ReadResult result = await reader.ReadAsync();

        // Tell the PipeReader how much of the buffer we have consumed
        reader.AdvanceTo(ProcessLines(result.Buffer));

        // Stop reading if there's no more data coming
        if (result.IsCompleted)
        {
            break;
        }
    }

    // Mark the PipeReader as complete
    reader.Complete();
}

private static SequencePosition ProcessLines(ReadOnlySequence<byte> sequence)
{
    BufferReader<byte> reader = new BufferReader<byte>(sequence);

    while (reader.TryReadTo(out ReadOnlySequence<byte> line, (byte)'\n'))
    {
        // Process the line
        ProcessLine(line);
    }

    return reader.Position;
}
```

[C# static local methods](https://github.com/dotnet/csharplang/issues/1565) will allow making this particular example even cleaner as you'll be able to pull the reader (which is `ref`) into a local method when using `async`.

To pause / recontinue reading the input data should be sliced. For example:

``` C#
public static ReadOnlySequence<byte> DoStuff(ReadOnlySequence<byte> data)
{
    BufferReader<byte> reader = new BufferReader<byte>(data);

    /* Do whatever */

    // Return the remaining data
    return data.Slice(reader.Position);
}
```

## Key design considerations

`BufferReader<T>` is designed with the following considerations.

1. It must be fast
    a. The current `ReadOnlySpan<T>` needs to be cached to achieve this (which necessitates `BufferReader<T>` being `ref`)
    b. Reading data that is constrained to a single segment should be as fast as possible.
2. There must be zero allocation alternatives for all functionality
    a. Using methods that don't return `ReadOnlySpan<T>` never heap allocate.
    b. `ReadOnlySpan<T>`
3. It should support UTF-8 and UTF-16 data
    a. Extension methods presume `BufferReader<byte>` has UTF-8 data, `BufferReader<char>` has UTF-16 data
    b. UTF-16 functionality currently blocked on `Utf16Parser` shipping.
4. It is constrained to `unmanaged` and `IEquatable<T>`
    a. `unmanaged` is necessary to do work on the stack (performance)
    b. `IEquatable<T>` is necessary to parse

